'''[[Pope John XXIII]]''' (25 November 1881 – 3 June 1963)  and '''[[Pope John Paul II]]''' (18 May 1920 – 2 April 2005) reigned as popes of the [[Roman Catholic Church]] and the sovereigns of [[Vatican City]] (respectively from 1958 to 1963 and 1978 to 2005). Their canonizations were held on 27 April 2014.<ref name="BBC">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-27172118 |title=Popes set for historic Vatican saints ceremony |accessdate=27 April 2014 |work=BBC News}}</ref> The decision to canonize was made official by [[Pope Francis]] on 5 July 2013 following the recognition of a miracle attributed to the intercession of John Paul II, while John XXIII was canonized for his merits of opening the [[Second Vatican Council]]. The date of the canonization was assigned on 30 September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/the-pope/10788640/Popes-John-Paul-II-and-John-XXIII-declared-saints.html|title= Popes John Paul II and John XXIII declared saints|date=27 April 2014|work=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702304788404579523802070217962|title= A Double Canonization for Popes John XXIII and John Paul II|date=27 April 2014|work=Wall Street Journal |accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref>

The Canonization Mass was celebrated by Pope Francis (with [[Pope Emeritus Benedict XVI]] concelebrating), on 27 April 2014 ([[Divine Mercy Sunday]]), in [[St. Peter's Square]] (Pope John Paul had died on the vigil of Divine Mercy Sunday in 2005).<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/apr/27/popes-john-paul-ii-and-john-xxiii-saints-canonisation|title= Popes John Paul II and John XXIII declared saints in double canonisation|first=Lizzy|last=Davies|date=27 April 2014|newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=29 April 2014|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://edition.cnn.com/2014/04/27/world/pope-canonization/|title= Sainthood for John Paul II and John XXIII, as crowds pack St. Peter's Square|date=27 April 2014|work=CNN|accessdate=29 April 2014|first1=Laura |last1=Smith-Spark|first2= Delia |last2=Gallagher|first3= Ben |last3=Wedeman}}</ref> About 150 [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]]s and 700 bishops concelebrated the Mass, and at least 500,000 people attended the Mass with an estimated 300,000 others watching from video screens placed around Rome.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://www.latimes.com/world/worldnow/la-fg-wn-pope-francis-canonization-vatican-20140427-story.html|first1=Patrick J.|last1= McDonnell |first2=Tom |last2=Kington|date=27 April 2014|location=Los Angeles, CA|title=Canonization of predecessors provides another boost for Pope Francis|quote=An estimated 800,000 people descended on Rome for the dual canonization, a Vatican spokesman said. That included the half a million around the Vatican and another 300,000 watching the event on giant TV screens set up throughout the city of Rome.}}</ref>

==People present at the canonization==
Delegations from over a hundred States or international organizations were present for the canonization in Rome, including 19 [[Head of state|heads of state]] and 24 [[Head of government|heads of government]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://visnews-en.blogspot.hu/2014/04/john-xxiii-and-john-paul-ii-inscribed.html |title=John XXIII and John Paul II Inscribed in the Book of Saints |accessdate=27 April 2014 |work=[[Vatican Information Service]]}}.</ref>

